            "id": "537000346f1e4d178d159",
            "questionText": "A car engine converts chemical energy from gasoline into mechanical work. For every $!$100 J$!$ of chemical energy input, the engine produces $!$30 J$!$ of useful mechanical work to propel the car, with the remaining $!$70 J$!$ lost as heat. The car, with a mass of $!$1200 kg$!$, then uses this mechanical work to accelerate from an initial speed of $!$10 m/s$!$ to a final speed. Calculate what is the final speed of the car, after using all $!$30 J$!$ of mechanical work from the engine.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "68598f79ad2a4f758d225",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by finding the initial kinetic energy of the car using its mass and initial speed. Identify the correct formula for kinetic energy.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "0f719348-94a2-4b8e-8cd8-638039f27e60"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$KE = \\frac{1}{2} mv^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$KE = mv^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$KE = mv$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "44bcca91d4eb463b97ab5",
                    "stepText": "Great, now that you have the formula, compute the initial kinetic energy by plugging in the values for mass (1200 kg) and initial speed (10 m/s). Then add the 30 J of work provided by the engine to obtain the final kinetic energy.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "60030"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "J",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "0f719348-94a2-4b8e-8cd8-638039f27e60"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "ba0076321cb24ad3b72b6",
                    "stepText": "Finally, using the relation between kinetic energy and speed, solve for the final speed of the car by rearranging the formula and taking the square root. Calculate the final speed.",
