        {
            "id": "739d6d0989ef49808b192",
            "questionText": "A cyclist pedals up a hill with a constant speed. The hill has a height of $!$50 m$!$, and the cyclist and bicycle combined have a weight of $!$700 N$!$. The cyclist's power output is $!$100 W$!$, and they take $!$60 \\text{ seconds}$!$ to reach the top of the hill. If the cyclist's body consumes $!$5000 J$!$ of energy during that time, determine the efficiency of the cyclist's energy conversion during this climb.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "2f321181cfcd4364a5a45",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by determining the mechanical work output. Which formula correctly relates work, power, and time?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "2691d473-fa9f-48af-866f-fcf735cf65ac"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$W = P \\times t$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$W = \\frac{P}{t}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$W = \\frac{t}{P}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "c5f9f52614ae48c380013",
                    "stepText": "Great, now that you have identified the relationship, use the formula $!$W = P \\times t$!$ to compute the work done by the cyclist. Use the values $!$P = 100\\,W$!$ and $!$t = 60\\,s$!$.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "6000"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "J",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "2691d473-fa9f-48af-866f-fcf735cf65ac"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "d231188c0bc44b8ba2702",
                    "stepText": "Next, we need to express the concept of efficiency. Which formula correctly represents efficiency in the context of energy conversion?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
